sation_list.rs` (lines 73–80)\n\nThe current comparator manually encodes \"descending by `Option<i64>`, with `None` sorted last.\" This is exactly what `sort_by_key` with `std::cmp::Reverse` and `Option` ordering achieves, since `None < Some(_)` under the standard `PartialOrd` for `Option`. Reversing `Some(t)` while leaving `None` would require a small wrapper, but the pattern is well-established and the intent becomes immediately readable:\n\n```rust\nself.conversations.sort_by_key(|c| {\n    c.last_message_time.map(std::cmp::Reverse)\n});\n```\n\nThis sorts `Some(Reverse(t))` in descending order of `t`, and `None` sorts after all `Some(...)` because `None < Some(...)` under `Option` ordering (which is then preserved since `Reverse` does not change the `None` case). The four-arm `match` with `std::cmp::Ordering::*` literal returns is less expressive than this idiom.\n\n---\n\n### 7. `get_or_create_conversation` has an unnecessary intermediate `get_mut` when the returned index is already known\n\n**File:** `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs` (lines 966–972)\n\n```rust\nif let Some(idx) = self.conversation_list.find_by_public_id(&public_id) {\n    if let Some(conversation) = self.conversation_list.get_mut(idx) {\n        conversation.id = contact_id;\n        conversation.name = display_name;\n    }\n    return idx;\n}\n```\n\n`find_by_public_id` returns `Some(idx)` only when the conversation exists, so `get_mut(idx)` can only return `None` if the index is out of bounds — which is impossible here. The inner `if let` is defensive noise. A direct `get_mut(idx).unwrap()` with an `expect` would communicate the invariant; alternatively, restructuring to avoid the double lookup (e.g., via `update_by_public_id` on `ConversationList`) would be cleaner. At minimum, a comment explaining why the inner `if let` is safe to elide would reduce confusion.\n\n---\n\n### Summary table\n\n| # | File | Severity | Issue |\n|---|------|----------|-------|\n| 1 | `app.rs` + `conversation_list.rs`